def absolute_value(val):
    a  = np.round(val/100.*data.dtypes.value_counts().sum(), 0)
    return a

Lasso¶

In [16]:
from sklearn.metrics import r2_score, mean_squared_error
In [18]:
from sklearn.linear_model import Lasso
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score
lasso_model = Lasso(alpha=0.1)
alphas = np.logspace(-5, 2, 200)
# Perform 10 fold cross validation and calculate the score alpha=np. logspace (-5, 2,200) to generate a series of alpha values
scores =[]
mse_scores =[]
# Construct an empty list to store the partial regression coefficients of the model
lasso_cofficients = []
mse_values = []
for alpha in alphas:
    lasso_model.alpha = alpha
    lasso = Lasso(alpha = alpha, normalize=True, max_iter=10000)
    cv_scores = cross_val_score(lasso_model,X,y, cv=10)
    scores.append(cv_scores.mean())
    lasso.fit(X, y)
    lasso_cofficients.append(lasso.coef_)
    mse_scores.append(cv_scores.mean())# Find the best alpha value with the highest cross validation score
    
    y_pred = lasso.predict(X)
    mse = mean_squared_error(y, y_pred)
    mse_values.append(mse)
best_alpha = alphas[np.argmax(scores)]
print(f"best alpha value : {best_alpha}")

best alpha value : 0.0013987131026472386
In [19]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(np.log10(alphas), mse_values, marker='o', linestyle='-', color='tab:red')
plt.xlabel('log()')
plt.ylabel('MSE')
plt.title('Lasso MSE vs. log(lambda)', size=20)
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()
